We're getting a little grain in the image and that's OK for now we'll talk about increasing the samples

06:28.820 --> 06:30.660
here in a minute but ok.

06:30.680 --> 06:34.930
We can kind of see what that point light is doing now.

06:34.940 --> 06:40.850
It's a little difficult sometimes or a little inconvenient to always come over here and hit the render

06:40.910 --> 06:41.300
button.

06:41.300 --> 06:49.770
Time and time again we have down here under this little menu the viewport shading we have a rendered

06:49.790 --> 06:51.490
viewport shading mode.

06:51.500 --> 06:57.820
And what this is is just an approximation of what you're going to see in the final render.

06:57.830 --> 07:00.560
So let me click on that.

07:00.750 --> 07:07.350
And now you can kind of get a sense of what the final render is going to look like from your normal

07:07.980 --> 07:10.030
viewport view here.

07:10.050 --> 07:18.060
Now I want to caution you that you should not use this and assume that this is the final way it's going

07:18.060 --> 07:18.890
to look.

07:18.960 --> 07:26.790
You should always do a final render with the render button over here at full resolution to make sure

07:26.790 --> 07:30.380
that what you think you're getting is actually what you're getting.

07:31.360 --> 07:38.090
Now I can come over here to this screen and go ahead and change this to the rendered viewport shading.

07:38.260 --> 07:47.320
And now I can come and change this back to solid so now as I work this view here is going to update

07:47.440 --> 07:48.500
automatically.

07:48.550 --> 07:55.160
So as I move the light around you can see the shadows move.

07:55.390 --> 08:00.340
You can see the difference in the lighting in real time.

08:00.340 --> 08:08.020
And this is going to be really handy as we begin to set up materials and the lighting of the scene.

08:09.280 --> 08:14.620
All right so I'm going to move this over just a little bit so that's kind of what we get with a point

08:14.620 --> 08:18.790
light or kind of open this up a little bit more and make it a little bit bigger.

08:18.790 --> 08:24.040
Let's do that if we wanted to make this light a little brighter in the scene we could come over to this

08:24.040 --> 08:30.640
panel right here with the point light selected I have a new panel here and I can click that and here's

08:30.700 --> 08:37.970
the point light and I can increase the intensity or the strength of the illumination here.

08:38.350 --> 08:45.850
So if I click and drag I can increase the amount of light or I can actually just plug in a number I'll

08:45.970 --> 08:48.920
type in 300 and there we go.

08:48.940 --> 08:52.660
So now we have a nice bright scene with our point light.

08:53.070 --> 08:57.340
Let's take a look at another kind of light with this in here.

08:57.340 --> 09:04.180
I could delete it and create a sun light or spotlight or any of these others but I can also come over

09:04.180 --> 09:09.010
here and you can see we've got these different buttons for sunspot himi and area.

09:09.010 --> 09:12.760
And I can just click on this and change it to sunlight.

09:12.850 --> 09:15.870
And now we've got a very bright sunlight.

09:15.880 --> 09:24.580
Let me turn it down back to 100 here and we go we've got a very bright sunlight shining down into our

09:24.590 --> 09:26.080
scene.

09:26.090 --> 09:36.370
Sunlight is basically an infinitely wide light object that is casting parallel rays down into the scene.

09:36.400 --> 09:45.310
It's like the sun in that the sun is just so big and so far away that the rays of light coming from

09:45.310 --> 09:48.960
it are virtually parallel when they hit the Earth.

09:48.970 --> 09:51.620
So that's what this is kind of imitating.

09:51.940 --> 09:57.630
So I could take this and I'll just move it up out here like this just so we can kind of see it.

09:57.850 --> 10:06.220
And the only thing that you can really adjust or alter with a sunlight is its rotation.

10:06.220 --> 10:08.380
So let me take this down.

10:08.380 --> 10:11.680
Let me take this down to say 30 so it isn't quite so bright.

10:12.150 --> 10:15.840
And if I hit R I can rotate it into the scene like this.

10:15.850 --> 10:23.620
And now it's shining directly into the scene let me take a strength down to one let me try that.

10:23.620 --> 10:24.590
There we go.

10:24.880 --> 10:31.760
So now you can see that it's just shining directly into the scene where we move this.

10:31.980 --> 10:37.170
You can see I can hit G and move it all around the scene and it doesn't do anything because it's just

10:37.170 --> 10:39.630
an infinitely wide object.

10:39.840 --> 10:44.300
And the only transfer we can adjust in the scene is the rotation.

10:44.310 --> 10:50.700
So it really doesn't matter where you put it so much as how you rotate it.

10:50.700 --> 10:57.530
So let me change from local to global and change to rotation.

10:57.540 --> 11:07.310
And if I move this around you can see now I'm pointing at this way and I can turn it like this and see

11:07.310 --> 11:11.170
the shadows change as I rotated around.

11:11.230 --> 11:15.340
Right.

11:15.480 --> 11:20.280
And we go but where I put it doesn't matter at all.

11:21.690 --> 11:28.320
All right well I'm going to put it back in the scene because I want to switch to a new light here.

11:29.920 --> 11:37.360
Move back over here and with that there I will switch to a spotlight now with a spotlight.

11:37.360 --> 11:42.710
I'm going to have to increase the intensity or the strength up quite a bit.

11:42.750 --> 11:48.530
Let me take this up to say 500 and I'll bring it down into the scene.

11:50.160 --> 11:53.750
Get it a little bit closer like this.

11:53.780 --> 11:59.660
OK so for this particular light it matters where you put it.

11:59.660 --> 12:05.020
So it's position and the rotation will affect how it looks in the scene.

12:05.060 --> 12:09.780
We have a couple of extra settings here for the spot shape.

12:09.860 --> 12:19.040
If I click and drag the size I can extend or increase the size of the cone or narrow it down very small

12:19.040 --> 12:24.400
so it's just pointing at one particular object like say just the bowl of fruit there.

12:25.890 --> 12:34.650
And in addition we have the blim that changes how the edge of the cone fades out or how sharp it is.

12:34.650 --> 12:44.290
So if I grab that blend and pull it up a bit you can see that that dissolve or fade is a lot softer

12:44.830 --> 12:52.570
or if I take it all the way back to zero it gives us a pretty hard edge on that spot.

12:52.570 --> 12:53.900
Now the Hami light.

12:54.100 --> 12:56.150
Let's take a look at that.

12:56.170 --> 13:00.760
If we switch to the Hami this is an odd kind of a light.

13:00.820 --> 13:10.810
It is as if there is a huge half sphere over the scene shining light into this scene from every point

13:10.870 --> 13:12.150
on that sphere.

13:12.460 --> 13:19.620
So let me take this down to maybe one again and let's see where we go for my taste.

13:19.810 --> 13:24.830
The Hami light is not something that looks realistic.

13:25.210 --> 13:33.430
It's a light that I mainly use say when I'm texture painting in Blendr and I need to see the colors

13:33.460 --> 13:38.230
or the textures that I'm painting on the object in the viewport.

13:38.530 --> 13:44.530
If I'm looking for realistic lighting the Hemmy light doesn't really do it for me.

13:44.530 --> 13:47.480
So just a warning about that.

13:47.500 --> 13:51.430
And lastly the area light is one of my favorites.

13:51.430 --> 13:55.460
Let's go to that and once again I'll turn up the strength.

13:55.460 --> 13:57.620
I mean turn up to say 400.

13:57.670 --> 14:04.960
Now the area light I like because it allows you to adjust the quality of the shadows in the seams so

14:04.990 --> 14:13.450
if you notice here these shadows are pretty sharp but if I increase the size of the area light I can

14:13.450 --> 14:21.310
just click in the size field and increase it you can see here's the actual shape of the light as I increase

14:21.400 --> 14:22.390
the light.

14:22.510 --> 14:26.010
These shadows get softer and softer.

14:26.170 --> 14:34.510
And so this allows you to really tweak how these shadows look in your seam because if it's a scene where

14:34.810 --> 14:43.060
sunlight is streaming into a room the direct shadows from the sunlight are going to be pretty sharp.

14:43.150 --> 14:51.100
But the other shadows in the room that are being affected or being cast by more ambient soft light the

14:51.100 --> 14:53.140
edges will be a lot softer.

14:53.140 --> 15:01.240
So you can really detail the shadows in your scene based on the particular kinds of light.

15:01.240 --> 15:04.460
So I personally like the area of light quite a bit.

15:04.480 --> 15:04.770
